WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:04.680
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:25.520
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Good
afternoon/early evening.

00:00:25.520 --> 00:00:28.080
It's so great to have you all here.

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:31.240
I don't know if did any of
you catch the performance

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:32.570
in the afternoon already?

00:00:32.570 --> 00:00:37.220
Or are you here in anticipation
of tonight's performance?

00:00:37.220 --> 00:00:38.550
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Or
both performances?

00:00:38.550 --> 00:00:39.850
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Yeah.

00:00:39.850 --> 00:00:41.890
Yeah. Oh, good.

00:00:41.890 --> 00:00:45.690
My name is David Plylar and I'm
a music specialist at the Library

00:00:45.690 --> 00:00:51.100
of Congress and I'm here with two
special guests just to talk about--

00:00:51.100 --> 00:00:55.170
a bit about the history
of composing for dance

00:00:55.170 --> 00:00:56.470
at the Library of Congress.

00:00:56.470 --> 00:01:00.330
But also, to talk about what
is involved in that process

00:01:00.330 --> 00:01:03.800
of composing for dance, and
actually putting together a project

00:01:03.800 --> 00:01:06.730
like the one that we're all
being able to take part of,

00:01:06.730 --> 00:01:10.340
which is what the Martha Graham
Dance Company this weekend

00:01:10.340 --> 00:01:14.870
and actually over the past
week, which is involved--

00:01:14.870 --> 00:01:18.490
talks about Isamu Noguchi as well

00:01:18.490 --> 00:01:23.480
as some other aspects
of the Graham legacy.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:29.560
So, I'm pleased to have with me
Aaron Sherber, who is the conductor

00:01:29.560 --> 00:01:32.730
and music director
for these performances

00:01:32.730 --> 00:01:35.070
and with the Martha
Graham Dance Company.

00:01:35.070 --> 00:01:40.200
And he's been leading the way with
our musicians and you won't see him

00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:42.660
but he's in the pit
doing all the work.

00:01:42.660 --> 00:01:44.770
So, you know, with the musicians.

00:01:44.770 --> 00:01:47.880
And so, he offers a
very unique perceptive

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:49.270
that we'll be able to get.

00:01:49.270 --> 00:01:55.270
And then also, Libby Smigel who is
our new dance archivist curator.

00:01:55.270 --> 00:01:58.360
We're not sure we just
call her the dance person.

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:02.960
And she's been a delight to
have in the music division

00:02:02.960 --> 00:02:05.890
and will offer some
perspective from that side.

00:02:05.890 --> 00:02:08.090
So, before we get started,

00:02:08.090 --> 00:02:13.390 position:56%
what I thought we could do is maybe
just give a little bit of background

00:02:13.390 --> 00:02:18.680
on who you are, that
would be helpful.

00:02:18.680 --> 00:02:21.680
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: I come from
traipse and through a lot

00:02:21.680 --> 00:02:27.420
of different aspects of dance
and I realized I did work

00:02:27.420 --> 00:02:31.110
with a composer back in my
undergrad days, which are hard

00:02:31.110 --> 00:02:32.630
to remember at this point.

00:02:32.630 --> 00:02:37.060 position:56%
Where I was choreographing for a
production in Greek of "The Bacchae"

00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:40.930
and doing that for my senior
theses and working with the person

00:02:40.930 --> 00:02:45.690
in the music division, who is
doing her own senior theses

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:48.750
and was writing for the
dancing at the same time,

00:02:48.750 --> 00:02:51.090
and it didn't ruin our friendship.

00:02:51.090 --> 00:02:52.390
So, there was that.

00:02:52.390 --> 00:02:56.900
And then, I have also
gotten a PhD in drama.

00:02:56.900 --> 00:02:59.710
So, I am bringing that to the floor

00:02:59.710 --> 00:03:03.810
and my most recent work before
coming to the library in August,

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:07.510
I headed the Dance Heritage
Coalition, which was an association

00:03:07.510 --> 00:03:11.120
of dance archives and
museums and libraries

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:18.240
so that we will be saving better,
we hope, dance legacies for all.

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:22.750
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: I've been
with the Martha Graham Company

00:03:22.750 --> 00:03:25.580 position:56%
for almost 18 years, 1998 I started.

00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:28.260
And actually, my first performance
with the company was here

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:31.360
at the library and it was the
first time that we brought back

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:33.840
"Appalachian Spring"
since the premier.

00:03:33.840 --> 00:03:36.400
So, it was-- that was
quite something to step

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.530
into as my entre into that world.

00:03:39.530 --> 00:03:44.000
I had no dance experience
as a conductor before that

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:46.580
but it gotten plenty
in the year since.

00:03:46.580 --> 00:03:49.370
And along the way, one
of the interesting things

00:03:49.370 --> 00:03:54.120 position:56%
about my job has been-- because of
the way the Graham Company is setup,

00:03:54.120 --> 00:03:56.500
I'm essentially the
whole music department.

00:03:56.500 --> 00:04:00.300
So, it's part conductor, part
librarian, part archivist,

00:04:00.300 --> 00:04:04.400
part historian and it's been
just a real thrill for me to come

00:04:04.400 --> 00:04:08.060
into contact with these pieces
and find out what their history is

00:04:08.060 --> 00:04:10.050
and how all these things
come together.

00:04:10.050 --> 00:04:12.260
And it's also nice to be
back here at the Library.

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:13.560
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Well,
it's great to have you.

00:04:13.560 --> 00:04:16.090
And also, we'll talk
about this later perhaps

00:04:16.090 --> 00:04:17.390
where you're doing
some editorial work--

00:04:17.390 --> 00:04:18.690
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Yeah.

00:04:18.690 --> 00:04:19.990
Uh-huh.

00:04:19.990 --> 00:04:21.290
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: -- as well.

00:04:21.290 --> 00:04:22.590
So, on some of these pieces.

00:04:22.590 --> 00:04:26.880
So maybe we'll start with hearing
just a sentimental recording.

00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:33.250
&gt;&gt; Which much affection,
Mrs. Coolidge.

00:04:33.250 --> 00:04:36.120
&gt;&gt; Do you remember
Elizabeth Sprague Coolidge?

00:04:36.120 --> 00:04:39.950
&gt;&gt; I certainly do and
with much affection.

00:04:39.950 --> 00:04:47.950
Mrs. Coolidge really made her
mark, I think, on American music.

00:04:47.950 --> 00:04:53.740 position:56%
In the consistent way over the
years, she established and continued

00:04:53.740 --> 00:04:58.090
to have here in Washington of
excellent chamber music concerts.

00:04:58.090 --> 00:04:59.760
We really owe her a great debt

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:02.630
and I'm very glad you've
given me the opportunity

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:04.690
to say that in public.

00:05:04.690 --> 00:05:12.130
I've often thought it and I wish
we had more Mrs. Coolidges around.

00:05:12.130 --> 00:05:16.930
&gt;&gt; That relationship is sort of
symbiotic in a way because just as,

00:05:16.930 --> 00:05:21.070
we, yourself, among the many
composers, owe a debt to her,

00:05:21.070 --> 00:05:25.160
I think, her memory owes quite
a debt to the man who composed

00:05:25.160 --> 00:05:27.510
"Appalachian Spring" for her.

00:05:27.510 --> 00:05:36.320
[ Applause ]

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:40.090
&gt;&gt; You're forgetting Martha
Graham who created the work.

00:05:40.090 --> 00:05:43.700
&gt;&gt; And it didn't even
have a title, did it?

00:05:43.700 --> 00:05:45.150
&gt;&gt; No, it didn't.

00:05:45.150 --> 00:05:47.610
I can't imagine that
being true any longer.

00:05:47.610 --> 00:05:50.200
I'm so used to thinking of
it as "Appalachian Spring".

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:52.930
It never occurred to me
that when I was writing it,

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:54.240
I didn't know what
she would call it.

00:05:54.240 --> 00:05:56.300
She hadn't given a name yet.

00:05:56.300 --> 00:06:00.020
So after finishing the work
and reading it back to her

00:06:00.020 --> 00:06:03.230 position:56%
when she already had it in rehearsal
the first time I said her--

00:06:03.230 --> 00:06:07.140
saw her, I said, "Martha, what
have you call the ballet?"

00:06:07.140 --> 00:06:10.690
I called it ballet for Martha
just so, you know, in my own mind.

00:06:10.690 --> 00:06:13.500
&gt;&gt; And that too-- That's exactly
what it says on the front page

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:15.870
of the manuscript,
ballet for Martha.

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:19.280
&gt;&gt; But that was the subtitle.

00:06:19.280 --> 00:06:20.580
No, I didn't have a title.

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:22.760
I was really putting
Martha Graham to music.

00:06:22.760 --> 00:06:25.290
I'd seen her dancing so many times.

00:06:25.290 --> 00:06:27.910
I had a sense of her
personality as a creative artist.

00:06:27.910 --> 00:06:31.560
I had a, really, in the front
of my mind, I wasn't thinking

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:35.000
about the Appalachians
or even spring.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:37.170
So, that I had no title for it.

00:06:37.170 --> 00:06:40.170
The first thing I said to her when
I came down to the rehearsal here

00:06:40.170 --> 00:06:43.060
in Washington was, "Martha,
what did you call the ballet?"

00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:45.500
She said, "Appalachian Spring."

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:46.800
Oh I said, "What a nice name.

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:48.600
Where did you get it?"

00:06:48.600 --> 00:06:52.070
[ Laughter ]

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:56.410
She said, "Well, it's a title
of a poem by Hart Crane."

00:06:56.410 --> 00:07:00.210
"Oh," I said, "Does the poem have
anything to do with the ballet?"

00:07:00.210 --> 00:07:01.510
She said, "No.

00:07:01.510 --> 00:07:03.010
I just like the title
and I took it."

00:07:03.010 --> 00:07:04.310
[ Laughter ]

00:07:04.310 --> 00:07:08.110
And over and over again,
nowadays, people come up to me

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:10.650
after seeing the ballet on
stage and say, "Mr. Copland,

00:07:10.650 --> 00:07:13.900
when I see that ballet and
when I hear your music,

00:07:13.900 --> 00:07:18.510
I can just see the
Appalachians and feel the spring."

00:07:18.510 --> 00:07:23.040
[ Laughing ]

00:07:23.040 --> 00:07:27.100
I began to see the
Appalachian myself a little bit.

00:07:27.100 --> 00:07:29.180
[ Laughter ]

00:07:29.180 --> 00:07:31.960
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: I have to add
two quick things about that.

00:07:31.960 --> 00:07:35.150
First of all, Copland
loved telling that story

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:38.250
and he told it almost
verbatim multiple times

00:07:38.250 --> 00:07:40.670
and I haven't heard the one
with the laugh track like that.

00:07:40.670 --> 00:07:41.970
So that's a new one.

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:43.270
But the second interesting thing

00:07:43.270 --> 00:07:47.420 position:56%
that I think even Copland either
may not be aware of or glossed over,

00:07:47.420 --> 00:07:53.250
it's not spring the season, it's
spring a body of water in the poem.

00:07:53.250 --> 00:07:55.470
And very few people
are aware of that.

00:07:55.470 --> 00:07:56.770
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: It's not--

00:07:56.770 --> 00:07:58.070
If I'm not mistaken,
it's also not the title.

00:07:58.070 --> 00:07:59.370
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: I know, it's
also not the title, I believe.

00:07:59.370 --> 00:08:00.670
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Yeah.

00:08:00.670 --> 00:08:01.970
It's--

00:08:01.970 --> 00:08:03.270
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Yeah,
it's in there.

00:08:03.270 --> 00:08:04.570
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar:
I have a colleague,

00:08:04.570 --> 00:08:05.870
a retired colleague
name Wayne Shirley

00:08:05.870 --> 00:08:09.870
who put together this really nice
overview of the whole process

00:08:09.870 --> 00:08:14.280
of commissioning "Appalachian
Spring" and also the other ballets

00:08:14.280 --> 00:08:20.750
that were-- or works that were
included on this event in 1944,

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:23.780 position:56%
that kind of goes into this in
great detail covering correspondence

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:25.080
and things like that.

00:08:25.080 --> 00:08:27.790
So, he addresses that
at that at one point.

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:31.760
You know, as funny as it is,
it actually brings up a lot

00:08:31.760 --> 00:08:37.940
of interesting issues that I think
are there from the onset of the--

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:41.250
at the beginning of
any great undertaking.

00:08:41.250 --> 00:08:44.530
And I consider any great
undertaking one that requires more

00:08:44.530 --> 00:08:47.170
than one person because you have
to come to terms with each other

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:49.100
in some way if you're going

00:08:49.100 --> 00:08:51.770
to create some meaningful
work of art together.

00:08:51.770 --> 00:08:56.730
And so, even something as seen
as kind of tangential or kind

00:08:56.730 --> 00:09:00.150
of after the fact as the title
of the work, that is the way

00:09:00.150 --> 00:09:03.450
that we have first access to
it in some-- in many ways.

00:09:03.450 --> 00:09:05.120
So, it's-- it ended up people--

00:09:05.120 --> 00:09:08.190
it has a certain resonance with
people today that, you know,

00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:11.710
if it were-- if it had a terrible
title, it wouldn't have helped it,

00:09:11.710 --> 00:09:14.960
you know, it's always nice that it
had this poetic component to it.

00:09:14.960 --> 00:09:19.390 position:56%
And one of the thing I just want to
mention about this and maybe, Aaron,

00:09:19.390 --> 00:09:22.570
you may be able to speak to
this as well, is that he did say

00:09:22.570 --> 00:09:25.420
that he didn't know what
Martha was going to call it.

00:09:25.420 --> 00:09:30.170 position:56%
That was the same, I think, the same
situation for the Hindemith work,

00:09:30.170 --> 00:09:33.200
"Herodiade" and the Milhaud work

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:34.640
because they were--
had different titles.

00:09:34.640 --> 00:09:36.250
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Well--
Though the Hindemith did not.

00:09:36.250 --> 00:09:38.930
The Hindemith I believe--
what do you have?

00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:40.230
You got something?

00:09:40.230 --> 00:09:41.530
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar:
"Mirror Before Me"?

00:09:41.530 --> 00:09:42.830
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: "Mirror
Before Me", oh you're right.

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:44.820
So, it was called "Herodiade"
ultimately because both Hindemith

00:09:44.820 --> 00:09:46.120
and Graham based their work

00:09:46.120 --> 00:09:48.830
on the Mellarme pros
and poem by that name--

00:09:48.830 --> 00:09:50.130
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Right.

00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:51.430
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: And I think it
just made more sense ultimately.

00:09:51.430 --> 00:09:52.730
I'd forgotten "Mirror Before Me."

00:09:52.730 --> 00:09:54.030
Yeah. But that, you
know, but the naming--

00:09:54.030 --> 00:09:56.140
that's not unusual that
the name comes last.

00:09:56.140 --> 00:09:57.440
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Sure.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:09:58.740
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: And in
fact, the world premiere,

00:09:58.740 --> 00:10:01.790
the Pontus Lidberg ballet didn't
have a name about 2 weeks ago

00:10:01.790 --> 00:10:04.250
when they had to print
it in the program.

00:10:04.250 --> 00:10:05.930
So, you know, that
fortuitous things.

00:10:05.930 --> 00:10:07.590
And the Barber that
were performing "Cave

00:10:07.590 --> 00:10:08.890
of the Heart" was originally called

00:10:08.890 --> 00:10:11.080
"Serpent Heart" when
it was premiered.

00:10:11.080 --> 00:10:14.120
Another Graham ballet "Diversion
of Angels" was originally called

00:10:14.120 --> 00:10:16.130
"Wilderness Stair"
when it premiered.

00:10:16.130 --> 00:10:20.920
So sometimes that process of
finding a name is, you know,

00:10:20.920 --> 00:10:23.320
it's the act of summing up
what it is you've created

00:10:23.320 --> 00:10:26.220
and sometimes it takes a little
while for that to settle in.

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:27.630
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar:
Well, there's also that

00:10:27.630 --> 00:10:30.830
and there's also what the
composer might call it on the side

00:10:30.830 --> 00:10:33.860
versus what the completed
work is called.

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:37.080
So like in the case of Milhaud
who had a piece that was also--

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:40.170
and he called it "Jeux de
Printemps" I think and then--

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:42.790
but went by the name
of "Imagined Wing".

00:10:42.790 --> 00:10:47.680
So, I think in his catalogue, he
kept it as with the French title

00:10:47.680 --> 00:10:51.430
but it-- so there's
different-- it never quite--

00:10:51.430 --> 00:10:52.730
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Right.

00:10:52.730 --> 00:10:54.030
And the Barber piece
is called "Medea".

00:10:54.030 --> 00:10:55.330
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Right.

00:10:55.330 --> 00:10:56.630
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: His-- The
published ballet is called "Medea".

00:10:56.630 --> 00:10:59.300
On the other hand, I think
people do make a little too much

00:10:59.300 --> 00:11:02.020
about the fact that Copland
titled it "Ballet for Martha"

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:04.840
because really, what else
was he going to call it?

00:11:04.840 --> 00:11:07.310
If you're writing a piece of
music and you're writing a ballet

00:11:07.310 --> 00:11:09.230
for Martha, you know,
that's what he put on.

00:11:09.230 --> 00:11:11.490
I don't think he ever
intended that to be a title.

00:11:11.490 --> 00:11:12.790
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Sure, sure.

00:11:12.790 --> 00:11:14.200
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: But I know
in all the Graham programs

00:11:14.200 --> 00:11:16.870
when we perform it, it always says
how Aaron Copland called it "Ballet

00:11:16.870 --> 00:11:19.380
for Martha" which Martha changed
it "Appalachian Spring" and I--

00:11:19.380 --> 00:11:22.350
at first, I think there's little
too much significance in that but--

00:11:22.350 --> 00:11:23.650
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Sure.

00:11:23.650 --> 00:11:24.950
Sure.

00:11:24.950 --> 00:11:26.250
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: Yeah.

00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:29.060
And actually, "House of
Victory" was one of the titles

00:11:29.060 --> 00:11:32.600
that Martha had settled
on in her iterations

00:11:32.600 --> 00:11:35.680
of sending scenarios
to Aaron Copland.

00:11:35.680 --> 00:11:38.720
And I think it's to his credit,
he didn't decide to adopt

00:11:38.720 --> 00:11:40.610
that one right away, you know.

00:11:40.610 --> 00:11:43.280
But she, you know, has
a handwritten, you know,

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:48.670
this is a working title and, you
know, I think it sort of still was

00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:53.130
in the process of being created
and it makes a lot of sense not

00:11:53.130 --> 00:11:54.430
to settle on something too soon.

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:55.730
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Well, sure.

00:11:55.730 --> 00:11:59.750 position:56%
And you know, and before we even get
to this process of getting created,

00:11:59.750 --> 00:12:02.530
you know, it's one thing
for friends to get together

00:12:02.530 --> 00:12:05.000
and put together, you know, a work.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:08.790
But it's another if you're talking
about professionals coming together

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:13.130
and working under contract and
having those types of issues

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:16.790 position:56%
that one must think about especially
with these larger works and these--

00:12:16.790 --> 00:12:20.920
the correspondence
and effort that goes

00:12:20.920 --> 00:12:25.150
into just the business end
of putting it together.

00:12:25.150 --> 00:12:28.260
I don't mean it in a crass
way, meaning like, it--

00:12:28.260 --> 00:12:34.740
there is a cost to hire 12
performers versus 5 performers.

00:12:34.740 --> 00:12:36.960
If you only have enough
money for five performers,

00:12:36.960 --> 00:12:40.480
chances are the piece will
probably only have five players.

