00:21:05.570 --> 00:21:11.350
If you go back to Graham's mentors,
Ruth St. Denis and Ted Shawn,

00:21:11.350 --> 00:21:12.920
and people-- other people
like Isadora Duncan,

00:21:12.920 --> 00:21:14.900
turn of the century modern dance,

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:16.950
the way they made a dance was
they'd find something nice

00:21:16.950 --> 00:21:20.500
by Satie [assumed spelling]
that has some full orientalism

00:21:20.500 --> 00:21:22.430
and they'd add some
scarves and some incense

00:21:22.430 --> 00:21:26.240
and they would decorate the music
and that was their idea, I mean,

00:21:26.240 --> 00:21:29.810
I'm simplifying a bit, but
they would decorate the music.

00:21:29.810 --> 00:21:31.910
And Horst was one of the
first people to say, "Yeah,

00:21:31.910 --> 00:21:34.790
if you want to be taken seriously,
if you want this modern dance

00:21:34.790 --> 00:21:36.210
to be taken seriously,

00:21:36.210 --> 00:21:38.760
the choreographer's
ideas have to come first.

00:21:38.760 --> 00:21:41.550
And you can't go find existing
music and fit your ideas it.

00:21:41.550 --> 00:21:45.940
