00:25:07.850 --> 00:25:13.020
And I've sort of wondered, you
know, whether just their location,

00:25:13.020 --> 00:25:18.980
when dance as a center in New
York seem to be so important that,

00:25:18.980 --> 00:25:20.740
you know, the ones
on the sort of edges,

00:25:20.740 --> 00:25:23.110
because San Francisco
had its stars too,

00:25:23.110 --> 00:25:24.990
which we just don't
know as much about.

00:25:24.990 --> 00:25:28.830
So, there are lots of things
to consider, but that's--

00:25:28.830 --> 00:25:30.130
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Yeah.

00:25:30.130 --> 00:25:31.430
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel -- that's a
really good question because--

00:25:31.430 --> 00:25:32.730
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar
That's-- that also--

00:25:32.730 --> 00:25:37.400 position:56%
speaking of that same thought was
actually articulated by Dakin Hearts

00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:40.190
at our Noguchi lecture
just the other night.

00:25:40.190 --> 00:25:48.180 position:56%
And he used images of these costumes
that Noguchi had designed for Page.

00:25:48.180 --> 00:25:52.630
But felt that, again, that part
of her regionalism was part

00:25:52.630 --> 00:25:55.500
of the reason that she wasn't
able to take off with--

00:25:55.500 --> 00:25:58.710
anyway, that's a bit
of in a side, but OK.

00:25:58.710 --> 00:26:03.330
But going back to maybe this, just
looking a bit more at this process

00:26:03.330 --> 00:26:08.020
of creation, the notion
of a scenario and what

00:26:08.020 --> 00:26:12.250
that tells a composer is
an interesting one to me

00:26:12.250 --> 00:26:15.410
because that does not strike me
as terribly specific in terms

00:26:15.410 --> 00:26:17.860
of what kind of information
is being conveyed.

00:26:17.860 --> 00:26:19.190
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Well, you need
you to look at the scenarios

00:26:19.190 --> 00:26:20.930
that Graham sent Copland.

00:26:20.930 --> 00:26:24.110
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Well, maybe
you can speak to that a bit.

00:26:24.110 --> 00:26:27.800
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: Well, she
started out with some curious ideas

00:26:27.800 --> 00:26:31.680
that might not be seemingly
a hit now.

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:35.550
There was a speaking character
in Native American that she had.

00:26:35.550 --> 00:26:38.180 position:56%
She had-- It was much more episodic.

00:26:38.180 --> 00:26:40.900 position:56%
So for example, there was an episode

00:26:40.900 --> 00:26:45.300
of John Brown's uprising
at Harpers Ferry.

00:26:45.300 --> 00:26:46.600
There was a lot.

00:26:46.600 --> 00:26:49.820
It could have been, you
know, a three-hour melodrama.

00:26:49.820 --> 00:26:52.640
And, you know, Copland would
write back and go, "Well,

00:26:52.640 --> 00:26:54.630
this is an interesting part."

00:26:54.630 --> 00:26:56.060
And kind of give her a feedback

00:26:56.060 --> 00:27:00.480
and she'd do another iteration
and kind of move along.

00:27:00.480 --> 00:27:05.160
In fact, I think she tried out
the "Medea" idea as well with him.

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:06.460
And he was like that's--

00:27:06.460 --> 00:27:07.760
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Right.

00:27:07.760 --> 00:27:09.060
Before they got to
"House of Victory".

00:27:09.060 --> 00:27:10.360
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: Exactly.

00:27:10.360 --> 00:27:11.660
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: She was very
interested in "Medea", but--

00:27:11.660 --> 00:27:12.960
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: In "Medea" and
he said, "That's really not me.

00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:14.260
That's not a good fit."

00:27:14.260 --> 00:27:15.560
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: She sent
him "Medea" in New England.

00:27:15.560 --> 00:27:18.300
So, it wasn't quite the
"Medea" that we got that far.

00:27:18.300 --> 00:27:19.600
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: No.

00:27:19.600 --> 00:27:20.900
No. Not at all.

00:27:20.900 --> 00:27:23.350
But at any rate, she sort
of would try out these ideas

00:27:23.350 --> 00:27:27.130
and I am a believer that
whether you're writing

00:27:27.130 --> 00:27:29.590
or choreographing a
good editor, when you--

00:27:29.590 --> 00:27:36.330 position:56%
trust is a great thing to have and I
think this is where we see a really,

00:27:36.330 --> 00:27:41.730
sort of a trustworthy relationship,
where she was getting back frank

00:27:41.730 --> 00:27:44.640
but very helpful feedback.

00:27:44.640 --> 00:27:48.060
And, you know, that played to both
of their strengths ultimately.

00:27:48.060 --> 00:27:50.510
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar Please go ahead.

00:27:50.510 --> 00:27:52.740
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: But the--
Then the interesting--

00:27:52.740 --> 00:27:56.410
the end to that though is, first of
all, if you look at the last script

00:27:56.410 --> 00:27:58.830
that she sent him and you
sit there with the score,

00:27:58.830 --> 00:28:02.680
you can through almost line by line
and see what Copland was doing.

00:28:02.680 --> 00:28:04.630
Copland, at this point,
he was working on--

00:28:04.630 --> 00:28:05.990
working a story out in Hollywood.

00:28:05.990 --> 00:28:07.930
He was doing film scores.

00:28:07.930 --> 00:28:13.500 position:56%
And so, he was basically scoring the
final scenario that Graham sent him.

00:28:13.500 --> 00:28:14.800 position:56%
And then, what's really interesting,

00:28:14.800 --> 00:28:17.130
not only did Copland not know the
name of the ballet until they got

00:28:17.130 --> 00:28:18.710
down here, he didn't even see it.

00:28:18.710 --> 00:28:20.870
He didn't see nothing of the
ballet until the dress rehearsal,

00:28:20.870 --> 00:28:22.690
the night before it opened.

00:28:22.690 --> 00:28:26.470
And what he didn't know was
when Graham got the score back,

00:28:26.470 --> 00:28:28.850 position:56%
it took her in different directions.

00:28:28.850 --> 00:28:32.430
And so, things that she described
in great detail to Copland,

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:35.730
she decided to do something
totally different with that music.

00:28:35.730 --> 00:28:38.470
He was OK with that though.

00:28:38.470 --> 00:28:39.920
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: I
think that your mentioning

00:28:39.920 --> 00:28:42.850
of film scoring though is an
important one just to bear

00:28:42.850 --> 00:28:46.910
in my mind in terms of that level
of trust that one must have,

00:28:46.910 --> 00:28:53.240
at some point, in terms of one's
ability to realize either something

00:28:53.240 --> 00:28:58.290
as scripted or a scenario that
is suggested versus the types

00:28:58.290 --> 00:29:02.530
of demands that he was becoming
used to in terms of the--

00:29:02.530 --> 00:29:06.430
meaning how you literally deal with
time and use those as constraints

00:29:06.430 --> 00:29:10.970
as opposed to necessarily-- things
that could be a bit more loose

00:29:10.970 --> 00:29:13.400
in terms of those timings.

00:29:13.400 --> 00:29:15.490
That's for composers.

00:29:15.490 --> 00:29:19.280
So especially, if you'd say
chamber music composers.

00:29:19.280 --> 00:29:23.230
Time is an issue but it's not
something that is so much,

00:29:23.230 --> 00:29:27.750
something that is prescribed
from on high,

00:29:27.750 --> 00:29:31.440
unless you're commissioning
agreements as, you know,

00:29:31.440 --> 00:29:33.160
that you have to have
a 23-minute work.

00:29:33.160 --> 00:29:35.290
But of course that
never works out anyway.

00:29:35.290 --> 00:29:38.190
But those-- Composers
respond very differently

00:29:38.190 --> 00:29:41.400
when they're collaborating
with others

00:29:41.400 --> 00:29:42.990
or if they're working
on a film score.

00:29:42.990 --> 00:29:46.920 position:56%
So it's just something to bear in
mind that it's a different type of--

00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:49.150
way of thinking about it and
some people are able to rise

00:29:49.150 --> 00:29:53.070 position:56%
to that challenge while others are--
don't that we usually don't hear

00:29:53.070 --> 00:29:54.650 position:56%
about those who don't, so that's OK.

00:29:54.650 --> 00:29:57.070 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Well, but that's--
I mean, that's Carlo Chavez, right

00:29:57.070 --> 00:29:59.680 position:56%
I mean, Graham sent him the scenario

00:29:59.680 --> 00:30:03.090
and when she finally got the music
back late, she listened to it

00:30:03.090 --> 00:30:05.810
and said, "This has nothing
to do with what I sent him.

00:30:05.810 --> 00:30:08.470
I can't possibly dance that dance."

00:30:08.470 --> 00:30:11.000
And so, she had to makeup
something completely different

00:30:11.000 --> 00:30:12.310
to go with that music.

00:30:12.310 --> 00:30:14.200
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar:
Speaking to that, I just--

00:30:14.200 --> 00:30:17.540
this kind of shows that I
have a review from the premier

00:30:17.540 --> 00:30:20.800
of the Chavez here
that I pulled out.

00:30:20.800 --> 00:30:26.180
This is not an advocation of the
content of it, but just rather

00:30:26.180 --> 00:30:28.620
to show what's on the issues were.

00:30:28.620 --> 00:30:35.400
It says, basically-- let's see.

00:30:35.400 --> 00:30:36.700
I'm sorry.

00:30:36.700 --> 00:30:38.000
"The work was commissioned

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:39.890 position:56%
for the Elizabeth Spring Collage
Foundation's festival at the Library

00:30:39.890 --> 00:30:43.530
of Congress in 1944, but Carlos
Chavez did not complete the musical

00:30:43.530 --> 00:30:44.830
score in time."

00:30:44.830 --> 00:30:47.780
So, this is common knowledge
apparently at this point.

00:30:47.780 --> 00:30:50.650
"Whether or not he has yet
completed, it would be difficult

00:30:50.650 --> 00:30:52.570
to answer from last
night's presentation.

00:30:52.570 --> 00:30:57.660
It is utterly without theatrical or
a choreographic quality, pure paper

00:30:57.660 --> 00:31:00.740
and ink music and long
stretches of it sound

00:31:00.740 --> 00:31:02.780
like so many pages
out of [inaudible]."

00:31:02.780 --> 00:31:05.200
That's a bit-- I don't feel
that way about [inaudible],

00:31:05.200 --> 00:31:08.110
either like it's not--
he's much malign.

00:31:08.110 --> 00:31:12.260
But-- sorry, the part I
wanted to get to you was that,

00:31:12.260 --> 00:31:14.610
"Ms. Graham has been able
to make a dance composition

00:31:14.610 --> 00:31:17.390
against it is inexplicable.

00:31:17.390 --> 00:31:20.910 position:56%
It's rhythmic plan and it's
phrasing are tenuous in the extreme.

00:31:20.910 --> 00:31:24.400
But she has justified them by
the almost constant employment

00:31:24.400 --> 00:31:26.910
of a free choreographic
counterpoint,

00:31:26.910 --> 00:31:29.740
which not only avoids
a totally static stage

00:31:29.740 --> 00:31:32.650
but actually creates
a certain excitement.

00:31:32.650 --> 00:31:36.400
What she has done is a miracle of
sheer invention, but invention not

00:31:36.400 --> 00:31:41.330 position:56%
on an intellectual plain, but on the
subjective level of pure intuition."

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:44.380
So, it's kind of an interesting
thing that there was a sense

00:31:44.380 --> 00:31:50.380 position:56%
of disjunction or something like
that that was perceived at that time

00:31:50.380 --> 00:31:52.520
but still an appreciation for what

00:31:52.520 --> 00:31:56.330
that final product
still ended up being.

00:31:56.330 --> 00:31:59.440
So, there you have that.

00:32:05.500 --> 00:32:07.230
So, one other-- all
right, let's see.

00:32:07.230 --> 00:32:12.790
I think that the-- I'll come
back and mention a few more

00:32:12.790 --> 00:32:15.660
of the other commissions
that have been done.

00:32:15.660 --> 00:32:19.260 position:56%
But I think one thing that would be
interesting to hear both of you talk

00:32:19.260 --> 00:32:22.070
about a bit more is-- OK.

00:32:22.070 --> 00:32:25.720
Let's say that there's this
agreement between choreographer

00:32:25.720 --> 00:32:29.120
and composer and things are moving
along and you get to a point,

00:32:29.120 --> 00:32:32.350
we'll even kind of gloss over
the stages of piano score

00:32:32.350 --> 00:32:37.530
versus having a full score if
it's differently orchestrated.

00:32:37.530 --> 00:32:41.780
What about the process of
rehearsal and putting it together?

00:32:41.780 --> 00:32:45.140
Maybe you can speak about some
of the challenges that come--

00:32:45.140 --> 00:32:47.650
that are maybe unique to dance

00:32:47.650 --> 00:32:51.330
and realizing these
types of new projects.

00:32:51.330 --> 00:32:53.860
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: Well,
from my standpoint, I'm--

00:32:53.860 --> 00:32:56.280
what I'm also seeing is that a lot

00:32:56.280 --> 00:33:02.050 position:56%
of people now are using recorded
music and dancers almost get a sense

00:33:02.050 --> 00:33:06.080
of even what the spaces
are between those pauses

00:33:06.080 --> 00:33:08.440
and it becomes very organic.

00:33:08.440 --> 00:33:16.640
And there's something lost,
I think, in terms of the sort

00:33:16.640 --> 00:33:20.150
of performative presence
of really being able

00:33:20.150 --> 00:33:23.200
to commune with the accompaniment.

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:26.220
Which isn't to say that they aren't
wonderful because oftentimes,

00:33:26.220 --> 00:33:30.200
they can't afford anything but
recorded music but, you know,

00:33:30.200 --> 00:33:34.240
I think we all even know on
our little iPhones, you know,

00:33:34.240 --> 00:33:38.940 position:56%
that we can even know how much space
it is before our next favorite song

00:33:38.940 --> 00:33:41.330
kicks in, what that time is.

00:33:41.330 --> 00:33:45.980
We get to know that and it
becomes then maybe more mechanical.

00:33:45.980 --> 00:33:52.500
And a number of choreographers such
as Mark Morris who likes to perform

00:33:52.500 --> 00:33:56.160
with the live music and tours
with, usually, with his own group

00:33:56.160 --> 00:34:01.600
if he can, is that he has them
record many different versions

00:34:01.600 --> 00:34:04.300 position:56%
and just pop these in as a surprise.

00:34:04.300 --> 00:34:06.770
So, you know, tonight,
we're using this one.

00:34:06.770 --> 00:34:10.860
And so, they get that sense that
it's still the same orchestration,

00:34:10.860 --> 00:34:15.760
it's the same set of musicians,
but that human thing of, you know,

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:20.340
never being able to do it exactly
the same a second time means

00:34:20.340 --> 00:34:22.230
that they have to be listening.

00:34:22.230 --> 00:34:26.720
And he really does respect
the musicality of dancers.

00:34:26.720 --> 00:34:28.090
And that's what he's also looking

00:34:28.090 --> 00:34:30.590
for when he's even
choosing his dancers.

00:34:30.590 --> 00:34:35.200
But, you know, then we have Merce
Cunningham, who works completely

00:34:35.200 --> 00:34:37.540
against that in a sense
that, you know,

00:34:37.540 --> 00:34:42.170
he doesn't let the dancers
do rehears to a, sort of,

00:34:42.170 --> 00:34:46.410
mechanical stopwatch-driven time.

00:34:46.410 --> 00:34:50.570
And that music is going to come--
or accompaniment or sound score

00:34:50.570 --> 00:34:54.590
or whatever it is that Merce
Cunningham would've commissioned

00:34:54.590 --> 00:35:00.190
that was made separately from
the dance and would be imposed

00:35:00.190 --> 00:35:03.190
at the same time for
the dress rehearsal.

00:35:03.190 --> 00:35:09.990
And then, he's hoping that
that internal ability to move

00:35:09.990 --> 00:35:14.310
and to hear it within yourself,
irrespective of what's happening

00:35:14.310 --> 00:35:17.720
on the outside or the
coughs in the audience,

00:35:17.720 --> 00:35:19.840
that it's going to be the same.

00:35:19.840 --> 00:35:23.440
And so, he's actually going for
something that's replicable,

00:35:23.440 --> 00:35:28.000
which is an interesting,
very different aesthetic.

00:35:28.000 --> 00:35:29.300
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: That's
interesting.

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:30.600
So, two things.

00:35:30.600 --> 00:35:31.990
So first of all, I was grinning

00:35:31.990 --> 00:35:33.290
when you told the story
about Mark Morris.

00:35:33.290 --> 00:35:36.980
I haven't heard that story but
that's been my dream for years.

00:35:36.980 --> 00:35:40.370
I mean seriously, because we--
the Martha Graham company,

00:35:40.370 --> 00:35:42.830
we perform with orchestra
whenever we can, but it's--

00:35:42.830 --> 00:35:44.610
it hasn't been nearly as
much as when I started.

00:35:44.610 --> 00:35:46.280 position:56%
And a lot of it has to do with money

00:35:46.280 --> 00:35:49.310
and they've got recordings
and it goes that way.

00:35:49.310 --> 00:35:51.530
And I've always thought, you know,
recordings wouldn't be so bad

00:35:51.530 --> 00:35:53.490
if you had a few different ones
where you can switch them up.

00:35:53.490 --> 00:35:55.950
So I think it's incredible
to hear that.

00:35:55.950 --> 00:36:01.550
The other thing with Merce
though is, Merce, I think,

00:36:01.550 --> 00:36:05.190
is creating the conditions
for the audience

00:36:05.190 --> 00:36:08.130
to have an artistic experience.

00:36:08.130 --> 00:36:13.930
So, for him, the-- in my
understanding, the dance

00:36:13.930 --> 00:36:18.100 position:56%
and the music happens simultaneously
but don't really relate other

00:36:18.100 --> 00:36:19.780
than the fact that they
may stop and start--

00:36:19.780 --> 00:36:21.520
start and stop at the same time.

00:36:21.520 --> 00:36:25.690
And for him-- you're right, I mean,
I've seen those dancers rehearse

00:36:25.690 --> 00:36:26.990
with the timings and
with all that so

00:36:26.990 --> 00:36:29.530
that they could do that repeatedly.

00:36:29.530 --> 00:36:35.030
And I think what's interesting for
him is how the audience perceive

00:36:35.030 --> 00:36:38.080
that interaction of
those two artistic things

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:40.440
happening simultaneously.

00:36:40.440 --> 00:36:42.840
But not really interacting.

00:36:42.840 --> 00:36:45.450
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: One question
about that is, is there--

00:36:45.450 --> 00:36:47.980
so saying the early
work of this nature,

00:36:47.980 --> 00:36:51.400
was their foreknowledge given
to an audience member or would--

00:36:51.400 --> 00:36:57.100
of this sense of lack of
intended interactivity

00:36:57.100 --> 00:36:59.390
versus whether they're
actually, you know--

00:36:59.390 --> 00:37:03.790
whether that coincides with what
they're actually experiencing?

00:37:03.790 --> 00:37:08.820
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: When he started
doing that, it was clear that he

00:37:08.820 --> 00:37:13.920
and the designer and the
composer would get together

00:37:13.920 --> 00:37:17.140
and they would talk about
what is the concept.

00:37:17.140 --> 00:37:20.440
So there would be a
concept and then agreed.

00:37:20.440 --> 00:37:22.700
And often oftentimes, the
title can give it away.

00:37:22.700 --> 00:37:24.000
You've got birds.

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:25.330
You've got island.

00:37:25.330 --> 00:37:27.150
You've got points in space.

00:37:27.150 --> 00:37:33.570
And, you know, you do see that
there are evocative parts in term--

00:37:33.570 --> 00:37:38.080 position:56%
when you hear the sound score or
you see the costumes as well as the,

00:37:38.080 --> 00:37:41.690
you know, whatever creature
movements that he has.

00:37:41.690 --> 00:37:49.680
But I do think it's-- it asks
something different, you're right,

00:37:49.680 --> 00:37:54.070
of the audience to-- that
it is a different kind

00:37:54.070 --> 00:37:55.390
of aesthetic experience.

00:37:55.390 --> 00:38:01.500
And it requires a different kind
of dancer because you almost have

00:38:01.500 --> 00:38:06.070
to train relational
phrasing out of you.

00:38:06.070 --> 00:38:11.980
It has to come just from the
body to body in space and not,

00:38:11.980 --> 00:38:14.080
you know, what you're hearing.

00:38:14.080 --> 00:38:15.840
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: But from the
standpoint of an audience number,

00:38:15.840 --> 00:38:19.560
those relationships, I think,
are constructed in the process

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:24.120
of experiencing the work
for whatever that's worth.

00:38:24.120 --> 00:38:27.200
And it might just be, you
know, that that's the end.

00:38:27.200 --> 00:38:28.500
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Right.

00:38:28.500 --> 00:38:30.100
And I think that's
what he was going for.

00:38:30.100 --> 00:38:33.450
I had a long discussion about
this with Beverly Emmons,

00:38:33.450 --> 00:38:34.850
wonderful lighting
designer for dance who've--

