01:04:03.120 --> 01:04:06.750
and this next one that she
wrote was, "And I don't know

01:04:06.750 --> 01:04:10.500
if we could afford a
Copland or a Hindemith."

01:04:10.500 --> 01:04:14.390
And in fact, she ended
up doing exactly that.

01:04:14.390 --> 01:04:19.380
But yes, it means budget it's,
you know, who's available?

01:04:19.380 --> 01:04:23.670
There was a World War II that was
brewing, which was another problem

01:04:23.670 --> 01:04:29.170
in terms of getting who was able,
you know, to agree to it and--

01:04:29.170 --> 01:04:30.470
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Yeah.

01:04:30.470 --> 01:04:31.770
I think one of the key
things, just to bear in mind

01:04:31.770 --> 01:04:34.740
about the entire process,
is that it doesn't work

01:04:34.740 --> 01:04:38.150
if the partners are not
excited about working together.

01:04:38.150 --> 01:04:41.530
Ultimately, if you have
an institution that wants

01:04:41.530 --> 01:04:47.050
to commission composer
X and choreographer Y,

01:04:47.050 --> 01:04:50.480 position:56%
if they are not interested in each
other, that's not-- it's not going--

01:04:50.480 --> 01:04:52.000
you're not going to have
something that's worth doing

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:53.780
and it probably will fall apart.

01:04:53.780 --> 01:04:57.570
So, there's this kind of dance
that happens where everybody's kind

01:04:57.570 --> 01:05:00.370 position:56%
of probably-- they don't want to say
that they really like this one close

01:05:00.370 --> 01:05:02.510
if the other person hates
it, you know, or that.

01:05:02.510 --> 01:05:07.830 position:56%
So this whole process goes about and
eventually things tend to go less

01:05:07.830 --> 01:05:10.750
around a particular partner
or things like that and then

01:05:10.750 --> 01:05:15.690
of course the greater stature
one has one more weight

01:05:15.690 --> 01:05:19.340
that opinion tends to have.

01:05:19.340 --> 01:05:23.580 position:56%
So, they're able to, you know, once
you have a commission with a Copland

01:05:23.580 --> 01:05:26.890
or a Hindemith then
you're able to work wisely

01:05:26.890 --> 01:05:30.290
with other composers later
too and there's other--

01:05:30.290 --> 01:05:31.590
&gt;&gt; Libby Smigel: Doors open.

01:05:31.590 --> 01:05:32.890
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Yeah.

01:05:32.890 --> 01:05:34.190
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: I'll add
just one very funny story.

01:05:34.190 --> 01:05:36.390
I think about the money
aspect of this.

01:05:36.390 --> 01:05:39.130
So Copland, I think,
was paid $500 I think?

01:05:39.130 --> 01:05:40.430
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: That's right.

01:05:40.430 --> 01:05:41.730
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: Is that true?

01:05:41.730 --> 01:05:43.030
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: Yeah.

01:05:43.030 --> 01:05:44.330
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: For
the commission for this.

01:05:44.330 --> 01:05:45.630
Which, you know, in the '40s was--

01:05:45.630 --> 01:05:46.930
it was not a small amount but
also he could have commanded more

01:05:46.930 --> 01:05:49.550
with his stature.

01:05:49.550 --> 01:05:52.150
When the Graham Company
performs "Appalachian Spring",

01:05:52.150 --> 01:05:56.090
because the music is copyrighted,
we pay a royalty every time

01:05:56.090 --> 01:05:59.640
through Boosey, to the
Aaron Copland Fund.

01:05:59.640 --> 01:06:02.050
And we also-- and we do it live,
you know, there's also a rental fee

01:06:02.050 --> 01:06:05.120 position:56%
to rent the actual parts and Boosey,

01:06:05.120 --> 01:06:07.470
because they understand
the popularity of this work

01:06:07.470 --> 01:06:10.800
and because they have a monopoly,
they tend to charge a lot

01:06:10.800 --> 01:06:12.180
of money for these things.

01:06:12.180 --> 01:06:16.810
I mean, we're talking something
like 3 or $400 per performance

01:06:16.810 --> 01:06:21.080
for royalty and another
400 for the parts rental.

01:06:21.080 --> 01:06:25.580 position:56%
We happen to find about a year ago,
I don't know if you know this story.

01:06:25.580 --> 01:06:28.690
We find a lot of interesting things
in our archives in our warehouse

01:06:28.690 --> 01:06:30.960
that surface after decades.

01:06:30.960 --> 01:06:34.340
There was a correspondence
between Martha and Aaron

01:06:34.340 --> 01:06:37.680
and we have a letter form Copland
that says, "Well, you know,

01:06:37.680 --> 01:06:41.210 position:56%
I know that money is difficult for
you and I'm so glad that you're able

01:06:41.210 --> 01:06:43.230
to have this piece out
there and perform it.

01:06:43.230 --> 01:06:45.000
And so, let's just
say between the two

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:48.510
of us $10 a performance
in perpetuity."

01:06:48.510 --> 01:06:51.050
[ Laughter ]

01:06:51.050 --> 01:06:55.170
So we took the letter to Boosey

01:06:55.170 --> 01:06:58.700
and they have their lawyers
look at it very carefully.

01:06:58.700 --> 01:07:03.080
And the lawyer said, "Well,
yeah, I guess that's it."

01:07:03.080 --> 01:07:07.170 position:56%
So, we don't get-- we're not getting
money back from them unfortunately.

01:07:07.170 --> 01:07:10.450
But now we pay them
$10 of performance.

01:07:10.450 --> 01:07:15.510 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: I notice they've
been downsized recently, is that--

01:07:15.510 --> 01:07:23.000
[ Inaudible Remark ]

01:07:23.000 --> 01:07:24.300
&gt;&gt; Aaron Sherber: OK.

01:07:24.300 --> 01:07:25.600
That's like a three-hour discussion

01:07:25.600 --> 01:07:32.580
but the short answer is the
composer has his own relationship

01:07:32.580 --> 01:07:37.590
with the publisher and the
copyright to the music travels--

01:07:37.590 --> 01:07:39.420
and it can be arranged differently.

01:07:39.420 --> 01:07:41.870
A commissioned organization
can undertake

01:07:41.870 --> 01:07:44.600
to own the rights to these things.

01:07:44.600 --> 01:07:46.680
But in general, and certainly
with all the Graham things,

01:07:46.680 --> 01:07:48.560
the copyright to the
music travels differently

01:07:48.560 --> 01:07:50.520
from the copyright to the dance.

01:07:50.520 --> 01:07:52.280
That's the very short answer.

01:07:52.280 --> 01:07:54.480
&gt;&gt; David H. Plylar: The difference
is if you have a work for hire,

01:07:54.480 --> 01:07:57.370
then the composer gives
up those rights.

01:07:57.370 --> 01:07:59.170
But the Library does not do that.

01:07:59.170 --> 01:08:00.700
So the composer always retains--

01:08:00.700 --> 01:08:03.960
or the creator of whatever work
is always retains those rights

01:08:03.960 --> 01:08:10.670
with certain allowances for, say,
broadcasters something like that.

01:08:10.670 --> 01:08:15.400
So, I think at this point because
there's a long night ahead,

01:08:15.400 --> 01:08:19.950
I'd like to thank our guests,
Aaron Sherber and Libby Smigel

01:08:19.950 --> 01:08:22.470
for joining me and having this
very interesting discussion.

01:08:22.470 --> 01:08:23.950
So, if you could join
me in thanking them.

